25183   // 1. store x, %p
25184   // 2. store y, %p+1
25185   // 3. store z, %p+2
25186   // 4. store a, %p
25187   // 5. store b, %p+3
25188   // - Scan this from the last to first store. The very first bunch of stores is
25189   // {5, {{4, -3}, {2, -2}, {3, -1}, {5, 0}}} (the element in SortedStores
25190   // vector).
25191   // - The next store in the list - #1 - has the same distance from store #5 as
25192   // the store #4.
25193   // - Try to vectorize sequence of stores 4,2,3,5.
25194   // - If all these stores are vectorized - just drop them.
25195   // - If some of them are not vectorized (say, #3 and #5), do extra analysis.
25196   // - Start new stores sequence.
25197   // The new bunch of stores is {1, {1, 0}}.
25198   // - Add the stores from previous sequence, that were not vectorized.
25199   // Here we consider the stores in the reversed order, rather they are used in
25200   // the IR (Stores are reversed already, see vectorizeStoreChains() function).
25201   // Store #3 can be added -> comes after store #4 with the same distance as
25202   // store #1.
25203   // Store #5 cannot be added - comes before store #4.
25204   // This logic allows to improve the compile time, we assume that the stores
25205   // after previous store with the same distance most likely have memory
25206   // dependencies and no need to waste compile time to try to vectorize them.
25207   // - Try to vectorize the sequence {1, {1, 0}, {3, 2}}.
